  "summary": "Hercule Poirot advises Colin Lamb to investigate a specific girl who may be connected to the case, noting that her presence at 19 Wilbraham Crescent was likely prompted by a specific phone call. Poirot suggests that Lamb visit a blind woman and visit a printing shop under the pretext of printing a manuscript to befriend the workers and gather information.\n\nDuring a trial in Crofton, Miss Weaver and Miss Martin provide testimony regarding a phone call received by the Cavendish Typewriting Agency. Miss Martin testifies that at 1:49 PM, a caller claiming to be Miss Pembroke requested that a stenographer, specifically Miss Weaver, go to 19 Wilbraham Crescent. However, Miss Pembroke denies making this call. Inspector Hatch testifies that he discovered the deceased's body at the residence immediately after receiving the call.\n\nDr. Riggs provides medical evidence, estimating the time of death occurred between 1:30 PM and 2:30 PM. He concludes the victim was stabbed in the heart with a thin, sharp knife, possibly a French cooking knife, while in a coma induced by chloral hydrate. The victim had not eaten solid food for at least four hours prior to death. The coroner adjourns the trial for fourteen days, rescheduling it for September 28. Following the proceedings, Irena Brent of the Cavendish Typewriting Agency attempts to locate Sheila, who reportedly left the court with a young man. Irena approaches a policeman to ask for Detective Hakast, who is seen discussing matters with the coroner and the county police chief.",
